The Child Fishermen who ply the waters of the Pacific off the coast of Peru and Ecuador have known for centuries about the El NiÃ±o.
Every three to five years during the months of December and January, fish in the coastal waters off of these countries virtually vanish, causing the fishing business to come to a standstill.
South American fishermen have given this phenomenon the name El NiÃ±o, which is Spanish for "The Child," because it comes about the time of the celebration of the birth of the Christ Child.
An understanding of the complex processes at work to produce the El NiÃ±o requires information about phenomena occurring all across the tropical Pacific, not just its eastern boundary, the west coast of South America.
Remote sensing, particularly from the weather satellites, has been the source of data that finally has made it possible to understand the interactions between atmospheric winds and oceanic temperatures and currents that lead to the El NiÃ±o.
Worldwide Effects El NiÃ±o effects are not limited to Ecuador.
They can be transmitparts of the world, the disruphave tragic and/or profound NiÃ±o has been shown to be flooding in Texas in the to the anomalous warmth Eastward east United States in the Currents Warm Surface Temperature
Nightly cloud images on television news from weather satellites show us the paths followed by the storms that cross the Pacific and travel northward from equatorial regions to the central lands of North America.
Important Weakened Trade indirect or secondary El NiÃ±o effects have been noted in other Winds locations worldwide.
During the 19821983 El NiÃ±o, there were huge drought-related fires in Borneo and Australia; drought-related eradication of sea bird populations on islands in the Pacific; flooding and landslides in Peru, Ecuador and in the Colorado River basin of the United States; 6 tropical cyclones in Tahiti; devastation of coral reefs throughout the Pacific; and drought, disease, and malnutrition in South Africa.
Closer to home El NiÃ±o years have been associated with changing North Pacific atmospheric and oceanic currents bringing warmer waters to the west coast of Washington, Oregon, and Callifornia.
These changes have been responsible for increased shark attacks off the Oregon coast, increased spinal injuries
The cycle of El NiÃ±o is completed as the weakened trade winds allow eastward currents to flow, carrying warm water from the western Pacific, and reinforcing the original warming trend.
