Ocean circulation moves 1/3 to 1/2 of the heat from the tropics toward the poles, moderating the climate at higher latitudes.
Ocean currents also transport and store dissolved gases, nutrients and other biochemical constituents.
Currents in the Northern Hemisphere flow in a clockwise direction and in the Southern Hemisphere they flow counterclockwise.
Variations in ocean currents in the tropics can lead to variations in global weather and rainfall patterns.
